{"title_page": "2020 Fiji Premier League", "text_new": "{{ infobox football league season\n| image                      = \n| caption                    = \n| competition                = 2020 Fiji Premier League\n| season                     = 2020\n| winners                    = \n| premiers                   = \n| promoted                   = \n| relegated                  = \n| continentalcup1            = [[2021 OFC Champions League|OFC Champions League]]\n| continentalcup1 qualifiers = \n| matches                    = \n| total goals                = \n| average goals              = \n| league topscorer           = \n| biggest home win           = \n| biggest away win           = \n| highest scoring            = \n| attendance                 = \n| average attendance         = \n| prevseason                 = [[2019 Fiji Premier League|2019]]\n| nextseason                 = [[2021 Fiji Premier League|2021]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 Fiji Premier League''' is the 44th season of the [[Fiji Premier League]] ('''Vodafone Premier League''' for sponsorship reasons), the top-tier [[association football|football]] league in [[Fiji]] organized by the [[Fiji Football Association]] since its establishment in 1977. It is scheduled to begin on 1 February 2020.<ref name=\"home\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020-vodafone-premier-league/|title=2020 Vodafone Premier League Draw|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref>[[Ba F.C.|Ba]] are the defending champions.\n\n==Team changes==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===To Fiji Premier League===\n\n'''Promoted from [[2019 Vodafone Senior League]]'''\n* [[Navua F.C.|Navua]]\n{{col-2}}\n\n===From Fiji Premier League===\n\n'''Relegated to [[2020 Vodafone Senior League]]'''\n* [[Tavua F.C.|Tavua]]\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Teams==\nA total of eight teams compete in the league.\n\n===Stadiums and locations===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Team\n! Location\n! Stadium\n! Capacity\n|-\n|[[Ba F.C.|Ba]]\n|[[Ba District, Fiji|Ba]]\n|[[Govind Park]]\n|align=center|13,500\n|-\n|[[Labasa F.C.|Labasa]]\n|[[Labasa]]\n|[[Subrail Park]]\n|align=center|10,000\n|-\n|[[Lautoka F.C.|Lautoka]]\n|[[Lautoka]]\n|[[Churchill Park (Lautoka)|Churchill Park]]\n|align=center|18,000\n|-\n|[[Nadi F.C.|Nadi]]\n|[[Nadi]]\n|[[Prince Charles Park]]\n|align=center|18,000\n|-\n|[[Nasinu F.C.|Nasinu]]\n|[[Nasinu]]\n|[[Nasinu Park]]\n|align=center|1,000\n|-\n|[[Navua F.C.|Navua]]\n|[[Navua]]\n|[[Thomson Park (Fiji)|Thomson Park]]\n|align=center|1,000\n|-\n|[[Rewa F.C.|Rewa]]\n|[[Nausori]]\n|[[Vodafone Ratu Cakobau Park]]\n|align=center|8,000\n|-\n|[[Suva F.C.|Suva]]\n|[[Suva]]\n|[[National Stadium (Suva)|ANZ Stadium]]\n|align=center| 30,000\n|}\n\n==Transfers==\nThe first transfer window of 2020 Fijian Football season opened on January 1 and finished on January 31.<ref name=\"fbcnews\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fbcnews.com.fj/sports/football/fiji-football-transfer-window-to-start-on-january-1st/|title=Fiji Football transfer window to open on January 1st|website=FBC News|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\nCurrent league champions [[Ba F.C.|Ba FC]] brought some important players like former [[Lautoka F.C.|Lautoka FC]] players [[Samuela Drudru]], [[Beniamino Mateinaqara]]<ref name=\"home2\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/19/samuela-drudru-and-mateinaqara-already-training-with-ba/|title=Drudru and Mateinaqara already training with Ba|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref> and [[Benjamin Totori]]. They have also signed with former [[Suva F.C.|Suva FC]] defender [[Laisenia Raura]].<ref name=\"home4\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/22/laisenia-raura-good-to-be-back-home/|title=Laisenia Raura: good to be back home|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref> Ni-Vanuatu forward [[Micah Tommy]] and Solomon Islands winger [[Darold Kakasi]] remained in the squad for 2020 season.<ref name=\"home5\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/21/darold-kakasi-is-back-to-ba/|title=Darold Kakasi is back to Ba|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\"home6\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/20/tommy-thomas-ni-vanuatu-power-in-ba/|title=Tommy &amp; Thomas: Ni-Vanuatu power in Ba|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref> They will also count on former [[New Zealand national football team]] head coach [[Ricki Herbert]] that signed a short-term contract with [[Ba F.C.|Ba FC]] until the end of [[2020 OFC Champions League]].<ref name=\"home7\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/25/ricki-herbert-to-ba-short-term-coaching-aiming-high-in-ofc-champions-league/|title=Ricki Herbert to Ba: short term coaching aiming high in OFC Champions League|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n[[Lautoka F.C.|Lautoka FC]] added some important players like former [[Ba F.C.|Ba FC]] winger [[Shazil Ali]], goalkeeper [[Joela Biuvania]] and Fiji U23 international [[Arami Manumanubai]]<ref>https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/02/09/lautoka-smashes-nadi-as-rewa-beats-nasinu-in-a-breathtaking-match-in-vodafone-premier-league/</ref> and Ni-Vanuatu forward [[Alex Saniel]]<ref>https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/02/02/alex-saniel-has-a-perfect-debut-for-lautoka/</ref>. They also hired Vanuatu international [[Jason Thomas (football)|Jason Thomas]]<ref>https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/02/07/jason-thomas-signs-for-lautoka/</ref> but he is not going to play the Vodafone Premier League.\n\n[[Suva F.C.|Suva FC]] also added some international power to their squad by bringing two Nigerian players: the defender [[Michael Oyesanya]] and the striker [[Jibola Afonja]] <ref name=\"home8\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/27/nigerian-duo-set-to-join-suva/|title=Nigerian duo set to join Suva|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref> that played the 2019 season for Samoan side [[Kiwi F.C.|Kiwi]]. However they lost Solomon Islands international [[Gagame Feni]] who moved to Vanuatu to play for [[ABM Galaxy F.C.|Galaxy]].\n\nCurrent [[Battle of the Giants (Fiji)|Battle of the Giants]], [[Inter-District Championship]] and [[Champion versus Champion (Fiji)|Champion vs Champion]] winners [[Labasa F.C.|Labasa FC]] managed to hold some key players like [[Siotame Kubu]] and [[Antonio Tuivuna]] that attracted the interest of [[Suva F.C.|Suva FC]] and [[Ba F.C.|Ba FC]] respectively.<ref name=\"home9\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/15/siotame-kubu-close-to-suva-move/|title=Siotame Kubu close to Suva move|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref><ref name=\"home10\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/23/labasa-and-ba-to-clash-in-fijian-cvc/|title=Labasa and Ba to clash in Fijian CVC|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref> They also brought [[Ratu Apenisa]] who scored two goals in the [[2020 Champion vs Champion]] against [[Ba F.C.|Ba]].<ref name=\"home11\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/26/ratu-anare-brace-gives-labasa-the-cvc-glory/|title=Ratu Anare brace gives Labasa the CVC glory|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref> Solomon Islands international [[Dennis Ifunaoa]] left the team to come back to his homeland to play for [[Solomon Warriors F.C.|Solomon Warriors]].<ref name=\"home12\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2019/11/09/benjamin-totori-and-dennis-ifunaoa-debut-for-solomon-warriors/|title=Benjamin Totori and Dennis Ifunaoa debut for Solomon Warriors|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n[[Nadi F.C.|Nadi FC]] will count on midfielder [[Avinesh Suwamy]] that left [[Ba F.C.|Ba]] after playing for the Men in Black for more than ten years.<ref name=\"home13\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/28/avinesh-suwamy-to-leave-ba/|title=Avinesh Suwamy to leave Ba|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n[[Nasinu F.C.|Nasinu FC]] lost young goalkeeper [[Mohammed Alzaar Alam]] who moved to New Zealand to play for [[Manukau United FC]].<ref name=\"home14\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/20/fijian-mohammed-alam-signs-with-new-zealand-club/|title=Fijian Mohammed Alam signs with New Zealand club|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref> However they added some good firepower by signing with three players from [[Solomon Islands]]: [[Atkin Kaua]], [[Jared Rongosulia]] and [[Marlon Nonone]].<ref>https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/02/05/kaua-and-more-two-solomon-islanders-to-sign-for-nasinu/</ref>\n\nRecently promoted [[Navua F.C.|Navua FC]] added some firepower by signing with [[2019 Vodafone Senior League]] top scorer [[Taniela Rakariva]].<ref name=\"home15\">{{cite web|url=https://oceaniafootballcenter.home.blog/2020/01/16/rakariva-strengthens-navua-attack-for-2020/|title=Rakariva strengthens Navua attack for 2020|website=Oceania Football Center|accessdate=2020-01-29}}</ref>\n\n==League table==\n<onlyinclude><!--To include this table in a page, use\n{{:2020 Fiji Premier League|transcludesection=League table}}\n-->{{#invoke:Sports table|main|style=WDL\n|section=League table\n|source=[https://www.fijifootball.com.fj/competition-list/vodafone-premier-league-2020-536399427/ Fiji FA]\n\n<!--UPDATE standings below (including date)-->\n|update=8 March 2020\n|win_BAF=1 |draw_BAF=0 |loss_BAF=0 |gf_BAF=1  |ga_BAF=0  |status_BAF= <!-- Ba -->\n|win_LAB=1 |draw_LAB=1 |loss_LAB=3 |gf_LAB=4  |ga_LAB=6  |status_LAB= <!-- Labasa -->\n|win_LAU=2 |draw_LAU=1 |loss_LAU=1 |gf_LAU=12 |ga_LAU=1  |status_LAU= <!-- Lautoka -->\n|win_NAD=2 |draw_NAD=0 |loss_NAD=2 |gf_NAD=7  |ga_NAD=8  |status_NAD= <!-- Nadi -->\n|win_NAS=1 |draw_NAS=1 |loss_NAS=3