ws)<ref name=\"MCS1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/lucifer/season-1 |title=Lucifer: Season 1 (2016)|publisher=[[Metacritic]] |accessdate=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#A01920;\"|\n| 2\n| 100% (9 reviews)<ref name=\"RTS2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s02 |title=Lucifer: Season 2 (2016 - 2017) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{n/a|TBD}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#76181D;\"|\n| 3\n| 100% (7 reviews)<ref name=\"RTS3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s03 |title=Lucifer: Season 3 (2017 - 2018) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{n/a|TBD}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#060606;\"|\n| 4\n| 100% (8 reviews)<ref name=\"RTS4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s04 |title=Lucifer: Season 4 (2019) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{n/a|TBD}}\n|-\n|}\n\nThe pilot episode was screened in July at the [[San Diego Comic-Con International|2015 San Diego Comic-Con]]. The pilot was met positively by the viewers, with [[Rich Johnston#Bleeding Cool|Bleeding Cool]]'s Dan Wickline praising the episode, saying \"the show itself is enjoyable because of the great dialogue and flawless delivery from its lead\" and \"This version of Lucifer refuses to take almost anything seriously and the show is better for it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2015/07/10/sdcc-15-pilot-screening-of-lucifer-an-invaluable-crime-fighting-tool/|title=SDCC '15: Pilot Screening of Lucifer&nbsp;\u2013 'An Invaluable Crime-fighting Tool' |publisher=Bleeding Cool|last=Wickline|first=Dan|date=July 10, 2015}}</ref>\nMax Nicholson of [[IGN]] rated the pilot episode a 6.9/10, praising Tom Ellis's performance as Lucifer and the lighthearted tone of the series, but criticizing the series for essentially being another crime procedural series.<ref>{{cite web |first=Max|last=Nicholson|website=IGN |title=LUCIFER: \"PILOT\" REVIEW |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/01/23/lucifer-pilot-review?abthid=56a3b4e2cdf0ee6f7f00000f|date=January 23, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first season received mainly negative reviews. The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 49% of critics gave it a positive review based on 43 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 5.36/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"''Lucifer''{{'s}} got sex appeal, but the show's hackneyed cop procedural format undermines a potentially entertaining premise.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s01 |title=Lucifer: Season 1 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 49 out of 100 based on 25 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/lucifer |title=Lucifer |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCritics have been much more receptive to the rest of the series. The second season currently has a 100% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 9 reviews, with an average rating of 7.83/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"Tom Ellis continues to shine as the Morning Star, though perhaps he could fly higher if he weren't locked into such a familiar format.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s02 |title=Lucifer: Season 2 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref> \n\nEd Power of the Telegraph gave the second-season premiere a 4/5, stating that \"It is entirely beguiled by its own preposterousness.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/lucifer-season-2-amazon-prime-review-a-wickedly-bonkers-run-in-w/|title=Lucifer season 2, Amazon Prime, review: a wickedly bonkers run-in with the mother from Hell|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> Bernard Boo of We Got This Covered gave the premiere 3.5/5 stars, saying \"Lucifer's second season gets off to a nice start, building on the show's strengths while retaining some of the weaknesses. It remains an unapologetically sordid, demonically fun hour of TV.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/tv/lucifer-season-2-review/|title=Lucifer Season 2 Review|publisher=We Got This Covered|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> LaToya Ferguson of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it a B, calling the episode funny with \"genuinely funny moments to come from\" and saying that the premiere \"starts the season off on a good note.\" She praised Tom Ellis' performance calling it \"pitch perfect.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/tvclub/lucifers-back-everythings-still-going-hell-242836|title=Lucifer's back, but everything's still going to Hell|website=The A.V. Club|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | Source(s)\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[2016 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| [[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]]\n| Choice TV: Breakout Star\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/771305/teen-choice-awards-2016-captain-america-civil-war-leads-second-wave-of-nominations|title=Teen Choice Awards 2016\u2014Captain America: Civil War Leads Second Wave of Nominations|last=Eliahou|first=Maya|website=[[E! Online]]|publisher=[[NBC Universal]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=June 18, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"row\" | ''Lucifer''\n| Choice TV: Breakout Show\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" rowspan=3| 2017\n| [[43rd People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Awards]]\n| Favorite TV Crime Drama\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://peopleschoice.com/2017/01/18/peoples-choice-awards-2017-winners/|title=People\u2019s Choice Awards 2017: Full List Of Winners|date=2017-01-19|work=People's Choice|access-date=2017-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[43rd Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n| Best Fantasy Television Series\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/saturn-awards-nominations-2017-rogue-one-walking-dead-1202000833/|title=Saturn Awards Nominations 2017: 'Rogue One,' 'Walking Dead' Lead|last=McNary|first=Dave|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 2, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Dragon Con#The Dragon Awards|Dragon Awards]]\n| Best Science Fiction or Fantasy Series\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Liptak|first1=Andrew|title=The 2017 Dragon Awards are a far-ranging sci-fi and fantasy reading list|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/4/16094656/dragon-award-dragoncon-sci-fi-fantasy-books-sad-puppies|website=The Verge|accessdate=4 August 2017|date=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Censorship campaign===\nOn May 28, 2015, the [[American Family Association]] (AFA) website [[American Family Association#One Million Moms/One Million Dads project|One Million Moms]] launched a petition to prevent the series' airing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsmax.com/Newsfront/lucifer-tox-tv-series-one-million-moms/2015/06/07/id/649257/|title=Fox's 'Lucifer' Series Draws Protests|publisher=newsmax.com|last=Richter|first=Greg|date=June 7, 2015}}</ref> The petition stated that the series would \"glorify Satan as a caring, likable person in human flesh.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/06/08/christian-group-one-million-moms-is-really-unhappy-about-the-new-lucifer-tv-show-5234872/ |title=Christian group One Million Moms is really unhappy about the new Lucifer TV show |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |last=Deen |first=Sarah |date=June 8, 2015}}</ref> It launched the petition and 31,312 people had signed it by the series' premiere date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://onemillionmoms.com/current-campaigns/urge-fox-drop-plans-to-air-lucifer-sign-petition-now/ |title=Urge FOX&nbsp;\u2013 Drop Plans to Air 'Lucifer'&nbsp;\u2013 Sign Petition Now! |publisher=One Million Moms |last= |first= |date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> Posted the same date on the main AFA website, the petition garnered 134,331 signatures by the premiere date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afa.net/action-alerts/fox-network-to-air-lucifer-portraying-satan-as-a-good-guy/ |title=FOX Network to air 'Lucifer'&nbsp;\u2013 portraying Satan as a good guy|publisher=[[American Family Association]] |last= |first= |date=May 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/one-million-moms-says-new-fox-tv-series-lucifer-mocks-the-bible-starts-petition-urging-for-shows-cancellation-139742/ |title='Lucifer' Fox TV Series 'Mocks the Bible,' Says One Million Moms' Petition to Cancel the Show |newspaper=[[The Christian Post]] |last=Smith |first=Samuel |date=May 29, 2015}}</ref> In response to the petition, character creator [[Neil Gaiman]] commented on his [[Tumblr]] page: \n{{quote|Ah. It seems like only yesterday (but it was 1991) that the \"Concerned Mothers of America\" announced that they were boycotting ''[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|The Sandman]]'' because it contained lesbian, gay, bi-sexual, and trans characters. It was [[List of The Sandman characters#Wanda|Wanda]] that upset them most: the idea of a trans-woman in a comic book... They told us they were organizing a boycott of ''The Sandman'', which they would only stop if we wrote to the American Family Association and promised to reform. I wonder if they noticed it didn't work last time, either...\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/lucifer/35580/lucifer-neil-gaiman-reacts-to-petition-against-tv-show |title=Lucifer: Neil Gaiman reacts to petition against TV show |publisher=[[Den of Geek!]] |last=Leane |first=Rob |date=June 1, 2015}}</ref>}} Regardless of the campaign, Fox renewed the series in April 2016 for a second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/lucifer-rosewood-renewed-season-2-fox-sleepy-hollow-grandfathered-the-grinder-new-girl-1201733778/|title='Lucifer', 'Rosewood' Renewed For Season 2 By Fox, Who's Still On the Bubble There?|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 7, 2016|accessdate=April 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation reactions===\nOn May 11, 2018, following the series' initial cancellation, co-showrunner Joe Henderson indicated that the third-season finale would feature a \"huge [[cliffhanger]]\" that was meant to deter [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] from cancelling the series and encouraged fans to \"make noise\" with the hashtag #SaveLucifer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/05/11/save-lucifer-fox-fan-campaign-twitter/|title='Save Lucifer!' Fans rally to rescue the Fox series from cancellation|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Gomez|first=Patrick|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/lucifer-canceled-reaction-joe-henderson-tom-ellis-heartbreaking-1202388736/|title=Canceled \u2018Lucifer\u2019 Producers, Cast Raise Hell On Social Media: \"Heartbreaking Doesn\u2019t Begin To Describe\"|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Evans|first=Greg|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Fans, as well as the cast and crew, rallied on [[Twitter]] and #SaveLucifer soon became the #1 trending topic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/tv-shows/2018/05/11/lucifer-cancelled-fox-fans-react/|title=\u2018Lucifer\u2019 Fans Are Angry As Hell About Show\u2019s Cancellation|website=Comicbook.com|last=Bonomolo|first=Cameron|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/hell-back-savelucifer-fan-crusade-burns-twitter-fox-213501289.html|title=To Hell and Back? #SaveLucifer Fan Crusade Burns up Twitter After Fox Cancellation|website=[[Yahoo!]]|last=Boucher|first=Ashley|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/tv-shows/2018/05/12/save-luficer-top-trending-lucifer-cancellation-fox/|title=#SaveLucifer Top Trend On Twitter After \u2018Lucifer\u2019 Cancellation|website=Comicbook.com|last=Bonomolo|first=Cameron|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> A second hashtag, #PickUpLucifer, emerged as a trending topic as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/689340/tom-ellis-lucifer-season-4-renewal-fans/|title='Lucifer' Star Tom Ellis 'Not Giving Up' on Season 4 Renewal, Cheers on Fans|website=[[TV Insider]]|last=Holbrook|first=Damian|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|author=Ildy Modrovich|user=Ildymojo|number=996195425429307393|title=Wait a sec... trending at #2 AND #5 worldwide!!! (Oh, and John Cena STILL wants to marry Nikki, if ya missed that too) #SaveLucifer #PickUpLucifer|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref> An online petition also began circulating aimed at renewing ''Lucifer'' for a fourth season on a new network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/05/11/lucifer-online-petition-renewed-season-4-canceled-/|title=Fans Create Online Petition to Get 'Lucifer' Picked Up By New Network|website=Comicbook.com|last=Cavanaugh|first=Patrick|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> [[Warner Bros. Television]] subsequently began shopping the series around to premium cable and streaming services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/save-lucifer-new-home-warner-bros-canceled-fox-1202388811/|title=#SaveLucifer: Can Warner Bros. TV Find New Home For Canceled Cult Favorite?|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2018/05/11/lucifer-twitter-raises-hell-over-foxs-drama-cancellation/604110002/|title='Lucifer': Twitter raises hell over Fox drama's cancellation|website=[[USA Today]]|last=Keveney|first=Bill|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2018/05/12/lucifer-dc-universe-streaming-service/|title=The DC Universe Streaming Service Could Save Lucifer|website=Comicbook.com|last=Drum|first=Nicole|date=May 12, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> On June 15, 2018, Netflix picked up the series for a fourth season.<ref name=\"Season4\" /> The penultimate episode of the fourth season is titled \"Save Lucifer\" in honor of the campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2018/11/06/lucifer-tv-series-season-4-episode-9-title-/|title='Lucifer' Episode 409 Has the Best Title Ever|website=Comicbook.com|last=Drum|first=Nicole|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Arrowverse==\n{{main|Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)}}\nLucifer Morningstar makes a cameo appearance in [[DC Comics]]' [[Arrowverse]] crossover event [[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|''Crisis on Infinite Earths'']], which is featured throughout the TV shows ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]], [[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]], [[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]], [[Batwoman (TV series)|Batwoman]], and [[Legends of Tomorrow]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2019/12/11/crisis-on-infinite-earths-spoilers-part-3-lucifer-cameo-tom-ellis/|title=Does Lucifer Appear in Crisis on Infinite Earths Part 3?|last=Drum|first=Nicole|date=December 10, 2019|work=comicbook.com|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref> The events are set in the five-year period of Lucifer's arrival on Earth, which is before the first season of ''Lucifer''. The event also retroactively establishes the world of the series as Earth-[[Number of the Beast|666]], and it confirms that Lucifer is aware of the [[Multiverse (DC Comics)|multiverse]].<ref name=\"ng20191210\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/crisis-on-infinite-earths-lucifer-star-tom-ellis-breaks-down-his-surprise-cameo-exclusive-137669 |title='Crisis on Infinite Earths': 'Lucifer's' Tom Ellis on Surprise Cameo |last=Ng |first=Philiana |date=2019-12-10 |website=Entertainment Tonight |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Television|United States}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Lucifer (TV series)}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.netflix.com/title/80057918|Official Netflix Website}}\n* {{IMDb title|4052886|Lucifer}}\n\n{{DC Comics TV}}\n{{Neil Gaiman}}\n{{Netflix original continuation series}}\n\n[[Category:Lucifer (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:2010s American television series]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American action television series]]\n[[Category:American fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Angels in television]]\n[[Category:Demons in television]]\n[[Category:The Devil in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Los Angeles Police Department]]\n[[Category:Fox Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Mythology in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Purgatory in fiction]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on DC Comics]]\n[[Category:Television series based on works by Neil Gaiman]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Television]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Television shows featuring audio description]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the 2016 TV series||Lucifer (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American television series for the Fox Broadcasting Company and Netflix (2016-present)}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Lucifer\n| image                    = Lucifer, title.jpg\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Urban fantasy]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Martin |first1=Neal |title=The Best Urban Fantasy TV Shows Ever|url=https://www.npmartin.com/the-best-urban-fantasy-tv-shows-ever-updated-2018/ |website=NP MARTIN |date=9 December 2014}}</ref>\n}}\n| based_on                 = {{Based on|Characters created for [[Vertigo (DC Comics)|DC Comics' Vertigo]]|[[Neil Gaiman]]|[[Sam Kieth]]|[[Mike Dringenberg]]}}\n| developer                = [[Tom Kapinos]]\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]]\n* [[Lauren German]]\n* [[Kevin Alejandro]]\n* [[D. B. Woodside]]\n* [[Lesley-Ann Brandt]]\n* [[Rachael Harris]]\n* Scarlett Estevez\n* [[Kevin Rankin (actor)|Kevin Rankin]]\n* [[Tricia Helfer]]\n* [[Aimee Garcia]]\n* [[Tom Welling]]\n* [[Inbar Lavi]]\n}}\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Ben Decter\n* [[Jeff Russo]]\n* [[Marco Beltrami]]\n* Dennis Smith\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| language                 = English\n| num_seasons              = 4\n| num_episodes             = 67\n| list_episodes            = List of Lucifer episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Tom Kapinos\n* [[Ildy Modrovich]]\n* [[Len Wiseman]]\n* [[Jonathan Littman]]\n* [[Jerry Bruckheimer]]\n* Joe Henderson\n}}\n| producer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Alex Katsnelson\n* Michael Azzolino\n* Erik Holmberg\n* [[Karen Gaviola]]\n}}\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Los Angeles, California]]\n* [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]]\n}}\n| cinematography           = {{Plainlist|\n* Glen Keenan\n* Ryan McMaster\n* Tico Poulakakis\n* Stefan von Bjorn\n* Barry Donlevy\n* [[Christian Sebaldt]]\n}}\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Marc Pattavina\n* Ray Daniels III\n* Fred Peterson\n* Hector Carrillo\n* Matt Coleshill\n* Jill D'Agnenica\n}}\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera setup|Single-camera]]\n| runtime                  = 42\u201356 minutes\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Jerry Bruckheimer Television]]\n* [[Vertigo Comics|Vertigo]] ([[DC Entertainment]])\n* [[Warner Bros. Television]]\n}}\n| distributor              = [[Warner Bros. Television Distribution]]\n| picture_format           = {{Plainlist|\n* [[720p]] [[16:9]] ([[HDTV]])\n* [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[16:9]] [[Ultra-high-definition television|UHDTV]] in [[High-dynamic-range video|high dynamic range]])\n}}\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]] 5.1\n| channel                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] (2016\u201318)\n* [[Netflix]] (2019\u2013present)\n}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2016|1|25}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/title/80057918\n| production_website       = http://www.warnerbros.com/tv/lucifer\n}}\n\n'''''Lucifer''''' is an American [[television series]] developed by [[Tom Kapinos]] that premiered on [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] on January 25, 2016.<ref name=\"deadline\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/09/lucifer-show-pilot-dc-comics-fox-834452/|title=Fox Nabs DC Entertainment 'Lucifer' Drama From Tom Kapinos As Put Pilot|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=September 16, 2014|accessdate=September 16, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Premieredate\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2015/11/10/idol-new-girl-get-fox-winter-premiere-dates/75526282/|title='Idol,' 'New Girl' get Fox winter premiere dates|last=Keveney|first=Bill|website=[[USA Today]]|date=November 10, 2015|accessdate=November 10, 2015}}</ref> It is based on the [[Lucifer (DC Comics)|DC Comics character]] created by [[Neil Gaiman]], [[Sam Kieth]], and [[Mike Dringenberg]] taken from the comic book series ''[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|The Sandman]]'', who later became the protagonist of a spin-off comic book series, both published by [[DC Comics]]' [[Vertigo (DC Comics)|Vertigo]] imprint. The series is produced by [[Jerry Bruckheimer Television]], [[DC Entertainment]] and [[Warner Bros. Television]].\n\nThe series revolves around Lucifer Morningstar ([[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]]), the [[Lucifer (DC Comics)|Devil]], who abandons Hell for [[Los Angeles]] where he runs his own nightclub and becomes a consultant to the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]]. The ensemble and supporting cast include [[Lauren German]] as Detective Chloe Decker, [[Kevin Alejandro]] as Detective Daniel \"Dan\" Espinoza, [[D. B. Woodside]] as [[List of Lucifer characters#Amenadiel|Amenadiel]], [[Lesley-Ann Brandt]] as [[Mazikeen (comics)|Mazikeen]], and [[Rachael Harris]] as Dr. Linda Martin. Filming took place primarily in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] before production was relocated entirely to [[Los Angeles]], [[California]] beginning with the third season.\n\nThe first season received mixed reviews from critics, though subsequent seasons were better rated. The fourth season also received high ratings and critical acclaim. Many critics particularly praised Ellis' performance. Despite initially high viewership for its debut, ratings remained consistently low throughout the series' run on Fox. On May 11, 2018, Fox cancelled ''Lucifer'' after three seasons. A month later, [[Netflix]] picked up the series for a fourth season of ten episodes, which was released on May 8, 2019. On June 6, 2019, Netflix renewed the series for the fifth and expected to be final season of 16 episodes. However, in March 2020, Tom Ellis and other stars of the show were reported to have signed up for a sixth season to be produced by Netflix and Warner Bros. <ref>https://tvline.com/2020/03/04/tom-ellis-lucifer-season-6-contract-renewal-netflix/</ref> Official confirmation is yet to be received.  It was later reported that production has stopped near to the end of Season 5 due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 COVID-19 pandemic]] and studio closures.<ref>https://tvline.com/2020/03/13/the-flash-coronavirus-season-6-shut-down-production/</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series focuses on [[Lucifer (DC Comics)|Lucifer Morningstar]] ([[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]]), a beautiful and powerful angel who was cast out of [[Heaven]] for betrayal. As the [[Lucifer (DC Comics)|Devil]], he gets bored and unhappy as the Lord of Hell for millennia. He resigns to his throne in defiance to his father ([[Presence (DC Comics)|God]]) and abandons his kingdom for [[Los Angeles]], where he ends up running his own nightclub called \"Lux\". He becomes involved in a murder case with Detective Chloe Decker ([[Lauren German]]), and is subsequently invited to be a consultant to the [[Los Angeles Police Department|LAPD]]. Throughout the series, several celestial and demonic threats come to Los Angeles; at the same time, Lucifer and Chloe end up appreciating and being happy with each other.\n\n==Cast and characters==\n{{main|List of Lucifer characters}}\n* [[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]] as [[Lucifer (DC Comics)|Lucifer Morningstar]]: The Lord of Hell, who is bored with his life, abandons his throne and becomes a civilian consultant for the [[Los Angeles Police Department]] while running his own high-end nightclub called \"Lux\".<ref name=\"newsarama.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.newsarama.com/23659-lucifer-cast-for-new-fox-pilot.html|title=LUCIFER Cast For New FOX Pilot|publisher=Newsarama.com|last=Chris|first=Arrant|date=February 27, 2015}}</ref>\n\n*[[Lauren German]] as Detective Chloe Decker: Her late father was a [[LAPD]] officer, and she is a [[homicide detective]]. She solves crimes with Lucifer after he takes an interest in her once she appears to be immune to his abilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/lucifer-season-2-spoilers-what-happened-episode-10-fall-finale-quid-pro-ho-reveals-2452062|title='Lucifer' Season 2 Spoilers: What Happened In Episode 10? Fall Finale 'Quid Pro Ho' Reveals That Chloe Decker Is Special [RECAP]|date=November 29, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n*[[Kevin Alejandro]] as Detective Daniel \"Dan\" Espinoza: An LAPD homicide detective and Chloe's ex-husband. He is Trixie's father.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/07/kevin-alejandro-cast-lucifer-fox-recasting-1201466834/|title=Kevin Alejandro Joins Fox Series 'Lucifer' As Regular In Recasting|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=July 1, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[D. B. Woodside]] as [[List of cosmic entities in DC Comics#A|Amenadiel]]: An angel, Lucifer's older brother, and the eldest of all their siblings. He arrives in Los Angeles to encourage Lucifer to go back to Hell, and failing that, he attempts to force Lucifer back in different ways.<ref name=\"DCTVUniverse1\">{{cite web|url=http://dctvuniverse.com/2015/03/d-b-woodside-and-rachael-harris-board-lucifer/ |title=D.B. Woodside And Rachael Harris Board 'Lucifer' |publisher=DCtvuniverse.com |last=Yohannes |first=Alamin |date=March 14, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402110334/http://dctvuniverse.com/2015/03/d-b-woodside-and-rachael-harris-board-lucifer/ |archivedate=April 2, 2015 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n*[[Lesley-Ann Brandt]] as [[Mazikeen (comics)|Mazikeen]]: Confidante and devoted ally of Lucifer Morningstar, \"Maze\" for short. She is a demon who, having served as his head torturer, followed him from Hell to Los Angeles, and acted as a bartender and bodyguard at Lucifer's club. In the second season, Maze looks for a new direction on Earth and becomes a [[bounty hunter]].<ref name=\"brandt\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/03/lesley-ann-brandt-lucifer-fox-pilot-recasting-1201394166/|title=Lesley-Ann Brandt Joins 'Lucifer' Fox Pilot in Recasting|website=Deadline Hollywood|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=March 17, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Shaw-Williams|first1=Hannah|title='Lucifer' TV Show Recasts Maze with 'Gotham' Cast Member Lesley-Ann Brandt|url=https://screenrant.com/lucifer-tv-show-casting-maze-lesley-ann-brandt/|website=Screen Rant|accessdate=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n* Scarlett Estevez as Beatrice \"Trixie\" Espinoza: Chloe and Dan's daughter, who befriends Lucifer and Mazikeen.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2015/tv/news/fox-lucifer-minority-report-series-orders-1201491294/|title=Fox Adds DC Comics Drama 'Lucifer' & 'Minority Report' to 2015\u201316 Slate|magazine=Variety|last=Wagmeister|first=Elizabeth|date=May 8, 2015}}</ref>\n*[[Rachael Harris]] as Dr. Linda Martin: Lucifer's [[Stanford University|Stanford]]-educated [[psychotherapist]], who initially accepts \"payments\" from him in the form of sex.<ref name=\"DCTVUniverse1\" />\n*[[Kevin Rankin (actor)|Kevin Rankin]] as Detective Malcolm Graham: A police officer who was shot prior to the beginning of the series. He briefly died but was then brought back from hell by Amenadiel to kill Lucifer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/10/fox-lucifer-cast-kevin-rankin-tom-ellis-dc-comics-1201567570/|title=Fox's 'Lucifer' Casts Kevin Rankin |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=October 5, 2015}}</ref> (season 1)\n*[[Tricia Helfer]] as Charlotte Richards / \"Mum\": Lucifer and Amenadiel's mother and exiled wife of God, who has escaped her prison in Hell. She is described as \"the goddess of all creation\". On Earth, her soul occupies the body of Charlotte Richards, a murdered lawyer. After she leaves the universe at the end of the second season, the human Charlotte resurrects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tvline.com/2016/06/21/tricia-helfer-lucifer-season-2-mother-charlotte-devil/|title=Tricia Helfer Joins Lucifer Season 2 as Literally the Mother From Hell|work=TVLine|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|date=June 21, 2016}}</ref> (seasons 2\u20133; guest season 5<ref>{{cite web |title=3 Theories on How Tricia Helfer's Charlotte Is Returning for Lucifer Season 5 |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/lucifer-season-5-tricia-helfer-returning-charlotte/ |website=TVGuide |accessdate=October 15, 2019 |date=October 15, 2019}}</ref>)\n*[[Aimee Garcia]] as Ella Lopez: A forensic scientist for the LAPD.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/lucifer-adds-aimee-garcia-as-905925|title='Lucifer' Adds 'Dexter' Alum Aimee Garcia as Series Regular for Season 2|last1=Stanhope|first1=Kate|last2=Goldberg|first2=Lesley|website=The Hollywood Reporter|date=June 23, 2016|accessdate=May 30, 2017}}</ref> (season 2\u2013present)\n*[[Tom Welling]] as Lieutenant Marcus Pierce / [[Cain]]: A highly respected police lieutenant who oversees the work of Chloe, Dan, and Ella at the LAPD. He is revealed to be the immortal Cain, who is [[Adam and Eve]]'s son and [[Abel]]'s brother. He is the world's first murderer, condemned to wander the Earth forever with the [[Curse and mark of Cain|Mark of Cain]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/tom-welling-lucifer-fox-season-3-1202503702/|title=Tom Welling Joins Cast of 'Lucifer' for Season 3|first=Debra|last=Birnbaum|date=July 22, 2017|magazine=Variety|accessdate=August 15, 2017}}</ref> (season 3)\n*[[Inbar Lavi]] as [[Eve]]: The world's first female human, Cain's mother and former lover of Lucifer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbr.com/lucifer-producer-says-season-4-will-be-darker-sexier/|title=Lucifer Producer Says Season 4 Will Be 'Darker' & 'Sexier'|last=Liu|first=Narayan|website=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref> (season 4; recurring season 5)\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Lucifer episodes}}\nIn April 2016, Fox renewed the series for a second season, which premiered on September 19, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/06/fox-fall-premiere-dates-2016-1201774060/|title=Fox Sets Fall 2016 Premiere Dates, Goes For Traditional Rolloutx|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=June 16, 2016|accessdate=June 17, 2016}}</ref> On October 31, 2016, the series received a 22-episode full second season pickup by Fox.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefutoncritic.com/news/2016/10/31/fox-orders-full-second-season-of-lucifer-846212/20161031fox02/ |title=FOX Orders Full Second Season of \"Lucifer\" |website=The Futon Critic |date=October 31, 2016 |accessdate=November 4, 2016}}</ref> On February 13, 2017, Fox renewed the series for a third season initially of 22 episodes, which premiered on October 2, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/02/lucifer-renewed-season-fox-1201910648/|title='Lucifer' Renewed For Season 3 By Fox|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=February 13, 2017|accessdate=February 13, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Season3Premiere\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/tv/news/fox-fall-premiere-dates-1202475957/|title=Fox Sets Fall Premiere Dates, Including 'Empire,' 'The Gifted,' 'The Orville'|website=Variety|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|date=June 22, 2017|accessdate=June 22, 2017}}</ref> However, in March 2017, it was revealed that the final four episodes of the second season would be removed and placed in the third season to air, meaning that the second season would consist of 18 episodes and the third season would consist of 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/lucifer-supersized-season-3-4-season-2-episodes-migrate-2017-18-1202050153/|title='Lucifer' Season 3 To Be Supersized After 4 Season 2 Episodes Migrate To 2017-18|website=Deadline Hollywood|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=March 23, 2017|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/lucifer-season-2-cut-22-episodes-18-four-episodes-be-part-season-3-2514538|title='Lucifer' Season 2 Cut From 22 Episodes To 18; Four Episodes To Be Part Of Season 3|website=[[International Business Times]]|first=Camille|last=Heimbrod|date=March 24, 2017|accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> On January 22, 2018, writer [[Chris Rafferty]] indicated that the third season would instead contain 24 episodes.<ref name=\"Season3Episodes\">{{cite tweet |user=chris_rafferty |author=Chris Rafferty |number=955492049351884800 |title=#LUCIFER RETURNS TONIGHT \ud83d\ude08 You've seen 11 episodes this season, but we're JUST GETTING STARTED. Now that Pierce's secret is out, things start moving crazy fast in our remaining 13 EPISODES. You have NO idea what's coming... \ud83d\ude08\ud83d\ude08\ud83d\ude08 #LuciferSeason3 @LuciferonFOX |date=January 23, 2018 |accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn May 11, 2018, Fox canceled the series after three seasons, stating it was a \"ratings-based decision\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/lucifer-canceled-fox-1202800382/|title='Lucifer' Canceled After Three Seasons at Fox|last=Turchiano|first=Danielle|website=Variety|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/lucifer-canceled-lethal-weapon-clayne-crawford-ouster-recasting-fox-executives-reaction-1202390233/|title=Fox Brass On 'Lucifer' Cancellation & 'Lethal Weapon' Lead Recasting |last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=May 21, 2018}}</ref> Before the series' cancellation, co-showrunner, Ildy Modrovich, stated that the final two episodes produced would be moved to a potential fourth season.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=Ildymojo |author=Ildy Modrovich |number=979626887319248897 |title=Season finale was directed by @eagleegilsson actually! The last two episodes produced will air next season... WHEN we get it. Right??? Everyone cross fingers. @LuciferDaily #lucifer |date=March 30, 2018 |accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref> Instead, [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] broadcast both episodes on May 28, 2018, as a singular two-hour bonus episode.<ref name=\"ExtraEpisodes\"/>\n\nOn June 15, 2018, it was announced that [[Netflix]] had picked the series up for a fourth season of ten episodes, which was released on May 8, 2019.<ref name=\"Season4\">{{cite news|url=https://tvline.com/2018/06/15/lucifer-netflix-season-4-renewed-returning/|title=Lucifer Resurrected! Netflix Picks Up Season 4 of Cancelled Fox Drama|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|work=[[TVLine]]|date=June 15, 2018|accessdate=June 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://hiddenremote.com/2018/08/05/fox-netflix-lucifer-change/ |title=FOX and Netflix's reasons behind Lucifer decisions show something needs to change |website=HiddenRemote.com |first=Alexandria |last=Ingham |date=August 6, 2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"S4PremiereDate00007\">{{cite magazine|url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/10/lucifer-season-4-premiere-date-may-netflix/|title=Lucifer reveals season 4 premiere date on Netflix with a hot video|last=Agard|first=Chancellor|magazine=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=April 10, 2019|accessdate=April 10, 2019}}</ref> On June 6, 2019, Netflix renewed the series for a fifth and final season of ten episodes.<ref name=\"S5Renewal\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/06/lucifer-renewed-season-5-final-season-netflix-1202628454/|title='Lucifer' Renewed For Fifth & Final Season By Netflix|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=June 6, 2019|accessdate=June 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>https://comicbook.com/dc/2019/06/17/lucifer-season-4-final-episode-count-netflix/</ref> The episode count for the fifth season was later raised to 16.<ref>https://ew.com/tv/2019/07/26/netflix-lucifer-final-season-episodes/</ref> The final season will be released in two batches of eight episodes each.<ref name=\"SplitSeason5\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/lucifer-season-5-netflix-tom-ellis-16-episodes-release-date-a9175651.html|title=Lucifer season 5: Final episodes to be released in two batches of eight on Netflix, reveals Tom Ellis |last=Harrison|first=Ellie|website=The Independent|date=October 29, 2019|accessdate=October 31, 2019}}</ref>\n{{:List of Lucifer episodes}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\nIn September 2014, it was reported that DC and Fox were developing a television series based on the ''Sandman'' character Lucifer, as originally written by Neil Gaiman.<ref name=deadline/> The series is a \"loose adaptation\" of the original comic-book.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/news/a780636/tom-ellis-had-no-idea-that-lucifer-was-based-on-a-comic-book/|title=Tom Ellis had no idea that Lucifer was based on a comic|date=January 22, 2016|publisher=|accessdate=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2015, the series was officially picked up for 13 episodes for the [[2015\u201316 United States network television schedule|2015\u201316]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2015/05/09/fox-orders-minority-report-and-dc-comics-lucifer|title=FOX ORDERS MINORITY REPORT AND DC COMICS' LUCIFER|last=Goldman|first=Eric|date=May 9, 2015|accessdate=May 9, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LUCIFERwriters/status/699045580916391936|title=13 episodes in Season 1! #MuchMoreToCome |author=Lucifer Writers Room|date=February 15, 2015|accessdate=February 16, 2015}}</ref> Fox then hired ''[[Almost Human (TV series)|Almost Human]]'' alum Joe Henderson as showrunner, with Kapinos remaining on the series in a lesser capacity.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/05/joe-henderson-lucifer-showrunner-fox-1201423561/|title=Joe Henderson To Run Fox Drama 'Lucifer'|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=May 9, 2015|accessdate=October 31, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview, actress [[Lesley-Ann Brandt]] stated that production for the fifth and final season was \"99% finished,\" with production all completed except for half of the final episode before suspending production due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.etonline.com/lucifer-lesley-ann-brandt-teases-whats-to-come-in-season-5-and-a-possible-season-6-exclusive-143575|title='Lucifer': Lesley-Ann Brandt Teases What's to Come in Season 5 and a Possible Season 6 (Exclusive)|last=Kile|first=Meredith|date=March 24, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nIn February 2015, it was announced that [[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]] had been cast as Lucifer Morningstar, and that [[Tom Kapinos]] would write the pilot, to be directed by [[Len Wiseman]].<ref name=newsarama.com/> [[Lina Esco]] was originally cast as Maze (Mazikeen),<ref name=newsarama.com-2>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsarama.com/23694-lucifer-finds-its-female-lead.html|title=FOX Adds Female Co-Star To LUCIFER Pilot|work=[[Newsarama]]|last= Marston|first=George|date=March 4, 2015}}</ref> however, the role was later recast with [[Lesley-Ann Brandt]].<ref name=brandt/> [[Nicholas Gonzalez]] portrayed Dan in the pilot episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2015/07/kevin-alejandro-cast-lucifer-fox-recasting-1201466834/|title=Kevin Alejandro Joins Fox Series 'Lucifer' As Regular In Recasting|first=Nellie|last=Andreeva|date=July 1, 2015|publisher=}}</ref> In June 2016, it was announced that [[Tricia Helfer]] had been cast as Lucifer and Amenadiel's mother, Charlotte, and that she was to appear in multiple episodes in the second season.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ausiello|first1=Michael|title=Tricia Helfer Joins Lucifer Season 2 as Literally the Mother From Hell|url=http://tvline.com/2016/06/21/tricia-helfer-lucifer-season-2-mother-charlotte-devil/|website=TvLine|accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> The character was promoted to series regular in July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ausiello|first1=Michael|title=Lucifer Ups Tricia Helfer to Regular as the Mother From Hell&nbsp;\u2014 First Photo|url=http://tvline.com/2016/07/20/lucifer-season-3-tricia-helfer-mother-photo/|website=TVLine|accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> [[Aimee Garcia]] had also been cast as a regular in the second season, playing L.A.P.D.'s forensic scientist Ella Lopez.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mason|first1=Charlie|title=Lucifer Adds Aimee Garcia for Season 2|url=http://tvline.com/2016/06/23/lucifer-season-2-aimee-garcia-cast-fox/|website=TVLine|accessdate=August 8, 2016}}</ref> In August 2016, executive producer [[Ildy Modrovich]] announced the casting of [[Michael Imperioli]] as the angel [[Uriel]], Amenadiel and Lucifer's younger brother with \"a chip on his shoulder\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mitovich|first1=Matt Webb|title=Lucifer Season 2 Casts The Sopranos' Michael Imperioli as the Angel Uriel|url=http://tvline.com/2016/08/08/lucifer-season-2-michael-imperioli-cast-uriel/|website=TVLine|accessdate=August 11, 2016}}</ref> For the fourth season, [[Graham McTavish]] and [[Inbar Lavi]] were cast as Father Kinley and [[Eve]] respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mitovich|first1=Matt Webb|title=Matt's Inside Line: Scoop on Lucifer, S.H.I.E.L.D., Arrow, Magicians, NCIS, #OneChicago, Supernatural and More|url=https://tvline.com/2019/01/25/agents-of-shield-spoilers-season-6-coulson-dead/|website=TVLine|accessdate=January 29, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Longo|first1=Chris|title=Lucifer Season 4: Everything You Need to Know|url=https://www.denofgeek.com/us/tv/lucifer/274156/lucifer-season-4-release-date-cast-trailer-news|website=DenofGeek|accessdate=January 29, 2019}}</ref> For season 5, Netflix announced the casting of [[Matthew Bohrer]] as Donovan Glover.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=1176098357535813635|title=First new casting announcement for #LuciferSeason5 with Matthew Bohrer (@MatthewBohrer) in the role of Donovan Glover|author=What's on Netflix|user=whatonnetflix|date=September 23, 2019|accessdate=December 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming locations===\nAlthough the pilot was shot on location in [[Los Angeles]], the rest of the first season and the entirety of the second were filmed in [[Vancouver]], [[British Columbia]] with some exterior filming in Los Angeles. Production relocated to [[California]] beginning with the third season,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jayson|first1=Jay|title=Season 3 of Lucifer Moving Production to Los Angeles|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2017/03/05/season-3-of-lucifer-moving-production-to-los-angeles/|website=Comicbook.com|accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref> taking advantage of tax incentives provided by the [[California Film Commission]] under its \"Program 2.0\" initiative<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2017/03/legion-lucifer-the-affair-oa-get-california-tax-credits-tv-1202045586/|title='Legion,' 'The Affair,' 'Lucifer' & 'The OA' Among 15 TV Projects Receiving California Tax Credits|last=Patten|first=Dominic|date=March 17, 2017|website=Deadline Hollywood|accessdate=March 17, 2017}}</ref> and spending $92.1 million on production.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=2017 Television Pilot Report |url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/08/2017_TV_Production_Study_v5_WEB.pdf|publisher=FilmL.A. |page=16|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> Season four was also shot on location in Los Angeles, as well as at Warner Bros.' [[Warner Bros. Studios, Burbank|Burbank studio lot]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1123911/Lucifer-season-4-location-Where-is-Lucifer-filmed-Netflix-series-Los-Angeles-Tom-Ellis-LA|title=Lucifer season 4 location: Where is Lucifer filmed? Where's it set?|last=Debnath|first=Needs|date=May 8, 2019|website=Daily Express|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> spending $35.8 million on production.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=2018 Television Report |url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/2018_TV_Report-WEB.pdf|publisher=FilmL.A. |page=14|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Music===\nThe opening theme is a six-second clip from \"Being Evil Has a Price\", performed by the band [[Heavy Young Heathens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Being Evil Has a Price|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01HU6XZZI/ref=cm_sw_su_dp|website=Amazon.com|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref> In a lawsuit filed against [[Warner Bros.]], the song's composers, Robert and Aron Marderosian, claim the song has been used without giving them proper credit or a licensing agreement.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kenneally|first1=Tim|title=Warner Bros Hit With a Hell of a Lawsuit Over 'Lucifer' Theme Song|url=https://www.thewrap.com/warner-bros-hit-with-a-hell-of-a-lawsuit-over-lucifer-theme-song/|website=www.thewrap.com|accessdate=6 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nSeveral episodes include musical performances by Tom Ellis, although he has stated in interviews that while it is his vocals, the piano accompaniment seen on screen is not actually his.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiddenremote.com/2016/04/18/lucifer-star-tom-ellis-takes-us-hell-nice-way/|title='Lucifer' Star Tom Ellis Takes Us To Hell (In A Nice Way)|date=April 18, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Neil Gaiman is a fan of David Bowie, and some of Bowie's music has been used on the series (The illustration of Lucifer in the comics is also based on David Bowie).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techtimes.com/articles/127292/20160125/david-bowie-inspired-comic-book-character-lucifer.htm|title=How David Bowie Inspired The Comic Book Character Lucifer|first=Lauren|last=Keating|date=January 25, 2016|website=www.techtimes.com|publisher=Tech Times|accessdate=October 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align: center; float:right\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"padding:0 8px\" colspan=\"3\" | [[DVD]] and [[Blu-ray Disc|Blu-ray]] release dates\n|-\n! style=\"padding: 0 8px\"| [[DVD region code#1|Region 1]]\n! style=\"padding: 0 8px\"| [[DVD region code#2|Region 2]]\n! style=\"padding: 0 8px\"| [[DVD region code#4|Region 4]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#3D0102;\"|\n| [[List of Lucifer episodes#Season 1 (2016)|1]]\n| {{dts|August 23, 2016}}<ref name=\"S1HomeMedia\">{{cite web |last1=Anderson |first1=Derek |title=LUCIFER: THE COMPLETE FIRST SEASON Blu-ray / DVD Release Details & Cover Art - Daily Dead |url=https://dailydead.com/lucifer-complete-first-season-blu-ray-dvd-release-details-cover-art/ |website=Daily Dea