th:12px; background:#A01920;\"|\n| 2\n| 100% (9 reviews)<ref name=\"RTS2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s02 |title=Lucifer: Season 2 (2016 - 2017) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes]|accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{n/a|TBD}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#76181D;\"|\n| 3\n| 100% (7 reviews)<ref name=\"RTS3\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s03 |title=Lucifer: Season 3 (2017 - 2018) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{n/a|TBD}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#060606;\"|\n| 4\n| 100% (8 reviews)<ref name=\"RTS4\">{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s04 |title=Lucifer: Season 4 (2019) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref>\n| {{n/a|TBD}}\n|-\n|}\n\nThe pilot episode was screened in July at the [[San Diego Comic-Con International|2015 San Diego Comic-Con]]. The pilot was met positively by the viewers, with [[Rich Johnston#Bleeding Cool|Bleeding Cool]]'s Dan Wickline praising the episode, saying \"the show itself is enjoyable because of the great dialogue and flawless delivery from its lead\" and \"This version of Lucifer refuses to take almost anything seriously and the show is better for it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bleedingcool.com/2015/07/10/sdcc-15-pilot-screening-of-lucifer-an-invaluable-crime-fighting-tool/|title=SDCC '15: Pilot Screening of Lucifer&nbsp;\u2013 'An Invaluable Crime-fighting Tool' |publisher=Bleeding Cool|last=Wickline|first=Dan|date=July 10, 2015}}</ref>\nMax Nicholson of [[IGN]] rated the pilot episode a 6.9/10, praising Tom Ellis's performance as Lucifer and the lighthearted tone of the series, but criticizing the series for essentially being another crime procedural series.<ref>{{cite web |first=Max|last=Nicholson|website=IGN |title=LUCIFER: \"PILOT\" REVIEW |url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2016/01/23/lucifer-pilot-review?abthid=56a3b4e2cdf0ee6f7f00000f|date=January 23, 2016|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe first season received mainly negative reviews. The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports that 49% of critics gave it a positive review based on 43 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 5.36/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"''Lucifer''{{'s}} got sex appeal, but the show's hackneyed cop procedural format undermines a potentially entertaining premise.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s01 |title=Lucifer: Season 1 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=March 22, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned a score of 49 out of 100 based on 25 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/lucifer |title=Lucifer |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\nCritics have been much more receptive to the rest of the series. The second season currently has a 100% on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 9 reviews, with an average rating of 7.83/10. The site's critics consensus reads, \"Tom Ellis continues to shine as the Morning Star, though perhaps he could fly higher if he weren't locked into such a familiar format.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/lucifer/s02 |title=Lucifer: Season 2 |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]] |publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]] |accessdate=May 8, 2019}}</ref> \n\nEd Power of the Telegraph gave the second-season premiere a 4/5, stating that \"It is entirely beguiled by its own preposterousness.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/on-demand/0/lucifer-season-2-amazon-prime-review-a-wickedly-bonkers-run-in-w/|title=Lucifer season 2, Amazon Prime, review: a wickedly bonkers run-in with the mother from Hell|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> Bernard Boo of We Got This Covered gave the premiere 3.5/5 stars, saying \"Lucifer's second season gets off to a nice start, building on the show's strengths while retaining some of the weaknesses. It remains an unapologetically sordid, demonically fun hour of TV.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/tv/lucifer-season-2-review/|title=Lucifer Season 2 Review|publisher=We Got This Covered|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref> LaToya Ferguson of ''[[The A.V. Club]]'' gave it a B, calling the episode funny with \"genuinely funny moments to come from\" and saying that the premiere \"starts the season off on a good note.\" She praised Tom Ellis' performance calling it \"pitch perfect.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/tvclub/lucifers-back-everythings-still-going-hell-242836|title=Lucifer's back, but everything's still going to Hell|website=The A.V. Club|accessdate=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! scope=\"col\" | Year\n! scope=\"col\" | Award\n! scope=\"col\" | Nominee(s)\n! scope=\"col\" | Category\n! scope=\"col\" | Result\n! scope=\"col\" | Source(s)\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"|2016\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[2016 Teen Choice Awards|Teen Choice Awards]]\n| [[Tom Ellis (actor)|Tom Ellis]]\n| Choice TV: Breakout Star\n| {{nom}}\n| rowspan=\"2\" | <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/771305/teen-choice-awards-2016-captain-america-civil-war-leads-second-wave-of-nominations|title=Teen Choice Awards 2016\u2014Captain America: Civil War Leads Second Wave of Nominations|last=Eliahou|first=Maya|website=[[E! Online]]|publisher=[[NBC Universal]]|date=June 9, 2016|accessdate=June 18, 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" scope=\"row\" | ''Lucifer''\n| Choice TV: Breakout Show\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| scope=\"row\" rowspan=3| 2017\n| [[43rd People's Choice Awards|People's Choice Awards]]\n| Favorite TV Crime Drama\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=http://peopleschoice.com/2017/01/18/peoples-choice-awards-2017-winners/|title=People\u2019s Choice Awards 2017: Full List Of Winners|date=2017-01-19|work=People's Choice|access-date=2017-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[43rd Saturn Awards|Saturn Awards]]\n| Best Fantasy Television Series\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/awards/saturn-awards-nominations-2017-rogue-one-walking-dead-1202000833/|title=Saturn Awards Nominations 2017: 'Rogue One,' 'Walking Dead' Lead|last=McNary|first=Dave|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 2, 2017|accessdate=March 2, 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Dragon Con#The Dragon Awards|Dragon Awards]]\n| Best Science Fiction or Fantasy Series\n| {{nom}}\n| <ref>{{cite web|last1=Liptak|first1=Andrew|title=The 2017 Dragon Awards are a far-ranging sci-fi and fantasy reading list|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/8/4/16094656/dragon-award-dragoncon-sci-fi-fantasy-books-sad-puppies|website=The Verge|accessdate=4 August 2017|date=4 August 2017}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===Censorship campaign===\nOn May 28, 2015, the [[American Family Association]] (AFA) website [[American Family Association#One Million Moms/One Million Dads project|One Million Moms]] launched a petition to prevent the series' airing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsmax.com/Newsfront/lucifer-tox-tv-series-one-million-moms/2015/06/07/id/649257/|title=Fox's 'Lucifer' Series Draws Protests|publisher=newsmax.com|last=Richter|first=Greg|date=June 7, 2015}}</ref> The petition stated that the series would \"glorify Satan as a caring, likable person in human flesh.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/06/08/christian-group-one-million-moms-is-really-unhappy-about-the-new-lucifer-tv-show-5234872/ |title=Christian group One Million Moms is really unhappy about the new Lucifer TV show |newspaper=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |last=Deen |first=Sarah |date=June 8, 2015}}</ref> It launched the petition and 31,312 people had signed it by the series' premiere date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://onemillionmoms.com/current-campaigns/urge-fox-drop-plans-to-air-lucifer-sign-petition-now/ |title=Urge FOX&nbsp;\u2013 Drop Plans to Air 'Lucifer'&nbsp;\u2013 Sign Petition Now! |publisher=One Million Moms |last= |first= |date=June 10, 2015}}</ref> Posted the same date on the main AFA website, the petition garnered 134,331 signatures by the premiere date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.afa.net/action-alerts/fox-network-to-air-lucifer-portraying-satan-as-a-good-guy/ |title=FOX Network to air 'Lucifer'&nbsp;\u2013 portraying Satan as a good guy|publisher=[[American Family Association]] |last= |first= |date=May 27, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.christianpost.com/news/one-million-moms-says-new-fox-tv-series-lucifer-mocks-the-bible-starts-petition-urging-for-shows-cancellation-139742/ |title='Lucifer' Fox TV Series 'Mocks the Bible,' Says One Million Moms' Petition to Cancel the Show |newspaper=[[The Christian Post]] |last=Smith |first=Samuel |date=May 29, 2015}}</ref> In response to the petition, character creator [[Neil Gaiman]] commented on his [[Tumblr]] page: \n{{quote|Ah. It seems like only yesterday (but it was 1991) that the \"Concerned Mothers of America\" announced that they were boycotting ''[[The Sandman (Vertigo)|The Sandman]]'' because it contained lesbian, gay, bi-sexual, and trans characters. It was [[List of The Sandman characters#Wanda|Wanda]] that upset them most: the idea of a trans-woman in a comic book... They told us they were organizing a boycott of ''The Sandman'', which they would only stop if we wrote to the American Family Association and promised to reform. I wonder if they noticed it didn't work last time, either...\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.denofgeek.com/tv/lucifer/35580/lucifer-neil-gaiman-reacts-to-petition-against-tv-show |title=Lucifer: Neil Gaiman reacts to petition against TV show |publisher=[[Den of Geek!]] |last=Leane |first=Rob |date=June 1, 2015}}</ref>}} Regardless of the campaign, Fox renewed the series in April 2016 for a second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/04/lucifer-rosewood-renewed-season-2-fox-sleepy-hollow-grandfathered-the-grinder-new-girl-1201733778/|title='Lucifer', 'Rosewood' Renewed For Season 2 By Fox, Who's Still On the Bubble There?|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=April 7, 2016|accessdate=April 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Cancellation reactions===\nOn May 11, 2018, following the series' initial cancellation, co-showrunner Joe Henderson indicated that the third-season finale would feature a \"huge [[cliffhanger]]\" that was meant to deter [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] from cancelling the series and encouraged fans to \"make noise\" with the hashtag #SaveLucifer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2018/05/11/save-lucifer-fox-fan-campaign-twitter/|title='Save Lucifer!' Fans rally to rescue the Fox series from cancellation|website=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Gomez|first=Patrick|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/lucifer-canceled-reaction-joe-henderson-tom-ellis-heartbreaking-1202388736/|title=Canceled \u2018Lucifer\u2019 Producers, Cast Raise Hell On Social Media: \"Heartbreaking Doesn\u2019t Begin To Describe\"|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Evans|first=Greg|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> Fans, as well as the cast and crew, rallied on [[Twitter]] and #SaveLucifer soon became the #1 trending topic.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/tv-shows/2018/05/11/lucifer-cancelled-fox-fans-react/|title=\u2018Lucifer\u2019 Fans Are Angry As Hell About Show\u2019s Cancellation|website=Comicbook.com|last=Bonomolo|first=Cameron|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yahoo.com/entertainment/hell-back-savelucifer-fan-crusade-burns-twitter-fox-213501289.html|title=To Hell and Back? #SaveLucifer Fan Crusade Burns up Twitter After Fox Cancellation|website=[[Yahoo!]]|last=Boucher|first=Ashley|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/tv-shows/2018/05/12/save-luficer-top-trending-lucifer-cancellation-fox/|title=#SaveLucifer Top Trend On Twitter After \u2018Lucifer\u2019 Cancellation|website=Comicbook.com|last=Bonomolo|first=Cameron|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> A second hashtag, #PickUpLucifer, emerged as a trending topic as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvinsider.com/689340/tom-ellis-lucifer-season-4-renewal-fans/|title='Lucifer' Star Tom Ellis 'Not Giving Up' on Season 4 Renewal, Cheers on Fans|website=[[TV Insider]]|last=Holbrook|first=Damian|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|author=Ildy Modrovich|user=Ildymojo|number=996195425429307393|title=Wait a sec... trending at #2 AND #5 worldwide!!! (Oh, and John Cena STILL wants to marry Nikki, if ya missed that too) #SaveLucifer #PickUpLucifer|date=May 14, 2018|accessdate=May 15, 2018}}</ref> An online petition also began circulating aimed at renewing ''Lucifer'' for a fourth season on a new network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/2018/05/11/lucifer-online-petition-renewed-season-4-canceled-/|title=Fans Create Online Petition to Get 'Lucifer' Picked Up By New Network|website=Comicbook.com|last=Cavanaugh|first=Patrick|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> [[Warner Bros. Television]] subsequently began shopping the series around to premium cable and streaming services.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/05/save-lucifer-new-home-warner-bros-canceled-fox-1202388811/|title=#SaveLucifer: Can Warner Bros. TV Find New Home For Canceled Cult Favorite?|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2018/05/11/lucifer-twitter-raises-hell-over-foxs-drama-cancellation/604110002/|title='Lucifer': Twitter raises hell over Fox drama's cancellation|website=[[USA Today]]|last=Keveney|first=Bill|date=May 11, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2018/05/12/lucifer-dc-universe-streaming-service/|title=The DC Universe Streaming Service Could Save Lucifer|website=Comicbook.com|last=Drum|first=Nicole|date=May 12, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref> On June 15, 2018, Netflix picked up the series for a fourth season.<ref name=\"Season4\" /> The penultimate episode of the fourth season is titled \"Save Lucifer\" in honor of the campaign.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2018/11/06/lucifer-tv-series-season-4-episode-9-title-/|title='Lucifer' Episode 409 Has the Best Title Ever|website=Comicbook.com|last=Drum|first=Nicole|date=November 6, 2018|accessdate=November 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Arrowverse==\n{{main|Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)}}\nLucifer Morningstar makes a cameo appearance in [[DC Comics]]' [[Arrowverse]] crossover event [[Crisis on Infinite Earths (Arrowverse)|''Crisis on Infinite Earths'']], which is featured throughout the TV shows ''[[Arrow (TV series)|Arrow]], [[The Flash (2014 TV series)|The Flash]], [[Supergirl (TV series)|Supergirl]], [[Batwoman (TV series)|Batwoman]], and [[Legends of Tomorrow]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/dc/2019/12/11/crisis-on-infinite-earths-spoilers-part-3-lucifer-cameo-tom-ellis/|title=Does Lucifer Appear in Crisis on Infinite Earths Part 3?|last=Drum|first=Nicole|date=December 10, 2019|work=comicbook.com|accessdate=December 10, 2019}}</ref> The events are set in the five-year period of Lucifer's arrival on Earth, which is before the first season of ''Lucifer''. The event also retroactively establishes the world of the series as Earth-[[Number of the Beast|666]], and it confirms that Lucifer is aware of the [[Multiverse (DC Comics)|multiverse]].<ref name=\"ng20191210\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.etonline.com/crisis-on-infinite-earths-lucifer-star-tom-ellis-breaks-down-his-surprise-cameo-exclusive-137669 |title='Crisis on Infinite Earths': 'Lucifer's' Tom Ellis on Surprise Cameo |last=Ng |first=Philiana |date=2019-12-10 |website=Entertainment Tonight |language=en-US |access-date=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Television|United States}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Lucifer (TV series)}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.netflix.com/title/80057918|Official Netflix Website}}\n* {{IMDb title|4052886|Lucifer}}\n\n{{DC Comics TV}}\n{{Neil Gaiman}}\n{{Netflix original continuation series}}\n\n[[Category:Lucifer (TV series)| ]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:2010s American television series]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:American action television series]]\n[[Category:American fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Angels in television]]\n[[Category:Demons in television]]\n[[Category:The Devil in fiction]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Fictional portrayals of the Los Angeles Police Department]]\n[[Category:Fox Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:Mythology in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Purgatory in fiction]]\n[[Category:Television programs based on DC Comics]]\n[[Category:Television series based on works by Neil Gaiman]]\n[[Category:Television series by Warner Bros. Television]]\n[[Category:Television series produced in Vancouver]]\n[[Category:Television shows featuring audio description]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Los Angeles]]\n", "name_user": "Ameesh P", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lucifer_(TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "BeIN Sports", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=May 2018}}\n{{lowercase}}\n{{Split portions|BeIN Sports (Australian TV channel)|BeIN Sports (Middle East TV network)|BeIN Sports (Canadian TV channel)|BeIN Sports (French TV channel)|BeIN Sports (Asian TV network)|BeIN Sports (Spanish TV channel)|BeIN Sports (Turkish TV network)|BeIN Sports (American TV channel)|existing=y|discuss=Talk:BeIN Sports#Split discussion of September 2018|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox television channel\n| name              = beIN SPORTS\n| logofile          = BeIN Sports.png\n| logosize          = 220px\n| launch            = 1 June 2012\n| closed date       = \n| picture format    = [[2160p]] [[UHDTV]] <br> {{small|(downscaled to [[1080p]] and [[16:9]] [[576i]] for the [[HDTV]] and [[SDTV]] feeds, respectively)}}\n| share             = \n| share as of       =\n| share source      =\n| network           = \n| owner             = [[beIN Media Group]]\n| key people        = [[Nasser Al-Khelaifi]] (Chairman) Yousef Al-Obaidly (CEO)<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n| parent            = [[beIN Media Group]]\n| slogan            =  \n| motto             =\n| country           = \n| language          = Arabic <br> English <br> French <br> Indonesian <br> Malay <br> Thai <br> Cantonese/Mandarin <br> Tagalog <br>Turkish\n| broadcast area    = Middle East & North Africa <br> France <br> United States <br> Canada <br> Turkey <br> Australia <br> New Zealand <br> Hong Kong <br> Brunei <br> Malaysia <br> Singapore <br> Indonesia <br> Philippines <br> Cambodia <br> Laos <br> Thailand\n| affiliates        =\n| headquarters      = [[Doha]] (Arabia channels)<br>[[Miami]] (North America channels)<br />[[Paris]] (French channels)<br>[[Jakarta]] (Indonesian channels)<br />[[Istanbul]] (Turkish channels)<br />[[Bangkok]] (Thai channels)<br />[[Manila]] (Philippine channels)<br />[[Kuala Lumpur]] (Malay channels)<br />[[Hong Kong]] (Mandarin channels)<br />[[Sydney]] (Australian channels)\n| former names      = beIN Sport (2012\u20132013)<br>Al Jazeera Sport (in [[MENA]]) (2003\u20132013)<br>Lig TV (in Turkey) (2001\u20132017)\n| sister names      = [[beIN Sports (Middle East TV network)|beIN Sports MENA]]<br>[[beIN Sports (French TV channel)|beIN Sports France]]<br>[[beIN Sports (American TV channel)|beIN Sports USA]]<br>[[beIN Sports (Canadian TV channel)|beIN Sports Canada]]<br>[[beIN Sports (Australian TV channel)|beIN Sports Australia]]<br>[[beIN Sports (Spanish TV channel)|beIN Sports Spain]]\n| website           = {{URL|https://www.beinsports.com/}} \n| online serv 1     = [[beIN SPORTS CONNECT]]\n| online chan 1     = [https://connect.beinsports.com beIN SPORTS CONNECT]\n}}\n'''beIN Sports''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|i\u02d0|\u026a|n}} {{respell|BEE|in}}) is a global network of sports channels owned and operated by [[beIN Media Group]]. Its chairman is [[Nasser Al-Khelaifi]], and its CEO is Yousef Al-Obaidly.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=BeIN Media appoints Yousef Al-Obaidly to CEO |url=https://www.digitaltveurope.com/2018/11/05/bein-media-ups-yousef-al-obaidly-to-ceo/ |website=Digital TV Europe}}</ref>\n\nbeIN currently operates channels in the Middle East & North Africa, France, Spain, United States, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Turkey, Hong Kong, Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia, Philippines, and Thailand.\n\nIn France, where beIN Sports was launched for the first time, it holds the rights to broadcast major [[association football|football]] tournaments, including [[Ligue 1]], [[La Liga]], [[Serie A]], [[Bundesliga]] and the [[UEFA European Football Championship|European Football Championship]]. Along with [[Canal+]], beIN Sports also holds the rights to broadcast all the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] matches from 2021 to 2024.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/france-soccer-tv/update-1-vivendis-canal-and-bein-win-french-champions-league-rights-idUSL8N289348|title=UPDATE 1-Vivendi's Canal+ and BeIN win French Champions League rights|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States and Canada, beIN Sports holds the rights to broadcast [[La Liga]], [[Ligue 1]], [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|CONMEBOL World Cup Qualifiers]], [[Copa Libertadores]] and [[Football League Championship]] matches and [[Real Madrid TV]], in addition to the major motorcycle road racing championships ([[MotoGP]] and [[Superbike World Championship|World Superbike]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beINsports.tv/|title=beIN SPORTS \u2013 North America's Premier Sports TV Network|work=beIN SPORTS US|access-date=11 May 2015}}</ref> It launched two channels in the United States (English and Spanish), in August 2012, followed by a full channel in Canada, on 31 January 2014.\n\nIn Indonesia, beIN Sports holds the rights to broadcast [[La Liga]], [[Ligue 1]], [[Serie A]] (2013\u20132016, return in 2018), [[S\u00fcper Lig]] (2017\u201318 until 2021\u201322), [[A-League]] (starts 2017\u201318 season), [[FFA Cup]] (starts 2017 season), [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|CAF World Cup Qualifiers]], , [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), and more. In Malaysia, beIN Sports offers comprehensive coverage of European Football Leagues including La Liga, Ligue 1 and more.\n\nIn Hong Kong, beIN Sports holds the rights to broadcast [[Serie A]], [[Ligue 1]], [[Major League Soccer]] (MLS), [[A-League]] (starts 2017\u201318 season), [[FFA Cup]] (starts 2017 season), [[UEFA Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League]] and more. In Thailand, beIN Sports holds the rights to broadcast [[La Liga]] , [[Serie A]], [[Ligue 1]], MLS, [[S\u00fcper Lig]] (2017\u201318 until 2021\u201322), [[A-League]] (starts 2017\u201318 season), [[FFA Cup]] (starts 2017 season), and more.\n\nIn Australia, the channel was launched in late November 2014, following the acquisition of Setanta Sports Australia which was rebranded as beIN Sports.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hilliard|first=Mark|title=Setanta Sports Australia set to be sold to Al Jazeera|publisher=The Irish Times|date=14 August 2014|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/sectors/media-and-marketing/setanta-sports-australia-set-to-be-sold-to-al-jazeera-1.1897079|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> beIN Sports Australia holds the rights to broadcast [[UEFA Champions League]] (2015\u20132018),<ref>{{Cite web|title = SBS agrees broadcast deal with BeIn Sport for continued Champions League coverage \u2013 mUmBRELLA|url = http://mumbrella.com.au/sbs-agrees-boradcast-deal-with-bein-sport-for-continued-champions-league-coverage-307923|website = mUmBRELLA|access-date = 2016-02-01|language = en-US}}</ref> [[UEFA Europa League]] (2015\u20132018), [[Football League Cup|EFL Cup]], [[La Liga]], [[Serie A]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Perry|first=Kevin|title=Exclusive \u2013 A New Rival for Fox Sports in 2014|publisher=Nelbie|date=18 October 2013|url=http://nelbie.com/kevmarl/2013/10/18/exclusive-a-new-rival-for-fox-sports-in-2014|accessdate=19 August 2014}}</ref> [[Ligue 1]], [[Bundesliga]], [[Major League Soccer|MLS]], [[Copa Libertadores]] and [[Six Nations Championship|RBS Six Nations]]. On 14 March 2016, beIN Sports Australia expanded from one to three channels, all in HD, and as of 15 May 2016 has been made available to all [[Foxtel]] sport pack subscribers, rather than the original add-on cost for a single SD channel. Fetch subscribers still only have access to beIN Sports 1, which is an add-on cost each month.\n\nbeIN Connect, also known as beIN Sports Connect, is a subsidiary [[over-the-top content]] (OTT) service started in 2014. It allows users to watch live and on-demand video content from a Mac, Windows PC, mobile phone, Xbox 360, Xbox One, PlayStation 3 or PlayStation 4 via a broadband or Wi-Fi internet connection. On-demand content comprises sports highlights, movies, and TV shows. beIN CONNECT is available as a paid service in France, Spain, United States, Canada, Turkey (in 2017), [[Asia-Pacific]] (in 2017) and the [[MENA]] region.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newswire.ca/news-releases/bein-sports-to-launch-bein-sports-connect-515193371.html|title=beIN SPORTS to Launch beIN SPORTS CONNECT|publisher=Cision}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Al Jazeera Media Network]] entered the European television rights market in June 2011 when it purchased a package of live French football [[Ligue 1]] matches from 2012 to 2016 for [[\u20ac]]90 million a year. The deal makes them joint broadcasters of domestic top-flight football in France alongside long-term rights holders [[Canal+]].<ref name=\"snet\">{{cite web |title=Al Jazeera make move into Ligue 1 |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/930049/al-jazeera-make-tv-move-into-french-football?cc=5901 |date=2011-06-23 |publisher=[[ESPN Soccernet]] |first=Harry |last=Harris |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> The broadcaster also acquired the [[pay-TV]] rights to the [[UEFA Champions League]], [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] from 2012 to 2015, [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] and [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] in France.<ref name=\"ucl\">{{cite web |title=al-Jazeera Sport awarded media rights in France |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/events/tv/news/newsid=1728186.html |publisher=UEFA.com |date=2011-12-05 |accessdate=2012-04-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510003636/http://www.uefa.com/uefa/events/tv/news/newsid%3D1728186.html |archivedate=2012-05-10 }}</ref><ref name=\"uel\">{{cite web |title=2012\u201315 UEFA Europa League media rights deal announced in France |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/mediaservices/mediainformation/newsid=1755027.html |publisher=UEFA.com |date=2012-02-17 |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref><ref name=\"euros\">{{cite web |title=EURO 2012 and 2016 rights awarded in France |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/events/tv/news/newsid=1782340.html |publisher=UEFA.com |date=2012-04-10 |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> France was targeted as Al Jazeera's first entry into Europe due to the fact that there were no dedicated sports channels, unlike in the [[United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"reu3\">{{cite news |title=Al Jazeera seeks to build global brand in sports |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/05/24/us-aljazeera-sports-idUSBRE84N1HE20120524 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=2012-05-24 |first1=Leila |last1=Abboud |first2=Gwenaelle |last2=Barzic |accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref>\n\nThe name \"beIN Sports\" was first revealed in early 2012. According to [[Nasser Al-Khelaifi]], the director of Al Jazeera Sports, the name \"symbolises the mind of two channels aiming at bringing live and exclusive broadcasting of the biggest events.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Al Jazeera officially introduces 'beIN Sports' |url=http://mediame.com/news/announcement/al_jazeera_officially_introduces_beIN_sport |publisher=mediaME.com |date=2012-03-28 |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> Former Canal+ executive Charles Bietry was hired by Al Jazeera to launch the channels.<ref name=\"reu1\">{{cite news |title=Al Jazeera sees sporting chance of global media brand |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/04/02/aljazeera-sports-idUSL6E8ET9BX20120402 |agency=[[Reuters]] |date=2012-04-02 |first1=Leila |last1=Abboud |first2= Gw\u00e9na\u00eblle |last2= Barzic |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> The channels will be available on all [[cable television|cable]] and [[IPTV]] providers and select satellite providers.<ref>{{cite news |title=beIN Sports 1 & 2 to be delivered to 14M potential households |url=http://www.rapidtvnews.com/index.php/2012052522050/beIN-sport-1-a-2-to-be-delivered-to-14m-potential-households.html |publisher=Rapid TV News |date=2012-05-25 |first=Pascale |last=Paoli-Lebailly |accessdate=2012-05-29}}</ref> [[CanalSat]] \u2013 owned by [[Canal+ Group]] \u2013 has declined to carry the channels as of March 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Al-Jezira Sport s'appuie sur l'Espagnol Mediapro |url=http://www.lefigaro.fr/football/2012/03/14/02003-20120314ARTSPO00486-al-jezira-sport-s-appuie-sur-l-espagnol-mediapro.php |work=[[Le Figaro]] |date=2012-03-14 |first1= Paul |last1= Gonzal\u00e8s |first2=Engu\u00e9rand |last2=Renault |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref>\n\nbeIN Sports 1 was launched on June 1, 2012, in time to broadcast Euro 2012.<ref name=\"demarre\">{{cite news |title=beINSport 1 d\u00e9marre le 1er juin |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/Actualites/beINsport-1-demarre-le-1er-juin/276188 |work=[[L'Equipe]] |date=2012-04-10 |first=Etienne |last=Moatti |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> beIN Sports 2 commenced on July 27, 2012, in time to broadcast the French [[Ligue 2]] season, and before the start of the [[2012\u201313 Ligue 1]] season.<ref name=\"demarre\"/>\n\nIn June 2015, it was announced that [[Nasser Al-Khelaifi]] had plans to create the beIN Sports channel on TV operators to cable in Brazil<ref>[http://www.portalmidiaesporte.com/2015/06/dono-do-psg-pode-trazer-canal-bein.html PSG owner can bring beIN Sports channel to Brazil] '' Portal media sport '', 8 June 2015</ref>\n\n[[beIN Sports (Spain)|beIN Sports Spain]] officially began broadcasting on 1 July 2015, the date on which [[Gol Televisi\u00f3n]] ceased broadcasting all football games, which during the summer were in place under the slogan \"Change the game\", \"Cambia el juego\" in Spanish. Thanks to an alliance between [[Al Jazeera]] and [[Mediapro]], beIN Sports Spain offers [[UEFA Champions League]] (2015\u20132018), [[UEFA Europe League]] (2015\u20132018), [[UEFA Super Cup]] (2015\u20132017), [[Premier League]] (2015\u201316 season only), [[Serie A]], [[Primeira Liga]], [[Jupiler Pro League]], [[Ligue 1]], [[DFB Pokal]], [[Coupe de la Ligue]], [[KNVB Beker]], [[Johan Cruijff Shield]], [[Copa de Brasil]], [[CONCACAF Gold Cup]], [[Copa Libertadores]] and [[Copa Sudamericana]]. beIN Sports Spain can be viewed over the Internet, smart TV ([[LG]] and [[Samsung]]), PC, laptops, tablets, Smartphones (iOS/Android), PS3/PS4, [[Chromecast]], TV Operators ([[Orange S.A.|Orange]], [[Vodafone]] and [[Telecable]]) and online platforms (beIN Sports Connect, Total Channel and [[YouTube]]). On Wednesday August 19, due to the start of the playoffs of the UEFA Champions League, [[beIN Sports (Spain)]] begins to emit beIN Sports MAX (up to 8 simultaneous channels) to broadcast all matches of the UEFA Champions League and UEFA Europe League.\n\n[[beIN Sports (Spain)]] offers customers [[Gol Televisi\u00f3n]] lost up to 30 June 2015 an exclusive promotion to watch beIN Sports through beIN Sports CONNECT, and through the app \"TotalChannel\". It also offers channels like FOX, AXN, TNT, and the best entertainment channels in HD for \u20ac5/month for two months, then from the third month onwards \u20ac9.99/month. [[beIN Sports (Spain)]] developed a channel licensed for bars in [[Spain]] called \"beIN Sports BAR\". The channel stopped transmission on 9 August 2018.\n\nFor the 2016\u20132017 season and onwards, beIN Sports Spain has the television rights to [[La Liga]] (eight games a day, always one of Real Madrid or FC Barcelona) and [[Copa del Rey]].\n\nbeIN Media Group acquired [[Digiturk]] in July 2015.\n\nOn November 1, 2017, beIN Sports created an [[Olympic Channel]] in the Middle East and North Africa region.<ref>[http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/olympic-channel-announces-bein-tie-up] - Sam Carp, SportsPro, 4 September 2017</ref>\n\n==Programming==\n\n=== English-language service ===\nA list of the English-language service personalities, which broadcasts to the Middle East, North Africa, Australia and New Zealand\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Role !! Note\n|-\n| [[Richard Keys]] || Anchor || Presenter of [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] Football\n|-\n| [[Angus Scott (television presenter)|Angus Scott]] || Anchor || Presenter of [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] Football\n|-\n| [[Andy Gray (footballer, born 1955)|Andy Gray]] || Analyst || Analyst of English Premier League Football\n|-\n| [[Andy Kerr (television presenter)|Andy Kerr]] || Anchor || Presenter of ''The Club''\n|-\n| [[Nicola Crosby (television presenter)|Nicola Crosby]] || Anchor || Presenter of the ''Express''\n|-\n| [[Aarran Summers (television presenter)|Aarran Summers]] || Anchor || Presenter of the ''News''\n|-\n| [[Alex Leduc (television presenter)|Alex Leduc]] || Anchor || Presenter of the ''News'', ''Express'', and ''US Xtra''\n|}\n\n===Football===\nIn France, beIN Sports holds one of five rights packages for [[Ligue 1]] from 2012 to 2016 \u2013 the package consisting of Friday night and Sunday evening matches. The other four packages are held by [[Canal+]].<ref name=\"snet\"/> It also shows [[Ligue 2]] matches. For the [[UEFA Champions League]], it has the rights to broadcast all matches except the 13 weekly first-choice picks (yet to be awarded to any broadcaster as of April 2012) from 2012.<ref name=\"ucl\"/> It also owns the rights to all [[UEFA Europa League]] matches including the final.<ref name=\"uel\"/>\n\nAlso in France, beIN Sports and Canal+ also share the rights to [[Serie A]] and [[Bundesliga]] matches.<ref>{{cite news |title=Droits du foot : Canal+ et Al Jazeera enterrent (provisoirement) la hache de guerre |url=http://www.telesatellite.net/sur-les-transpondeurs/droits-du-foot-canal-et-al-jazeera-enterrent-provisoirement-la-hache-de-guerre/ |work=T\u00e9l\u00e9 Satellite et Num\u00e9rique |date=2012-03-09 |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> It also airs [[FA Cup]], [[Football League Championship]], [[La Liga]], [[Argentine Primera Divisi\u00f3n]]<ref>{{cite news|title=beIN Sports nets Argentinian football rights|url=http://www.sportspromedia.com/news/bein_sports_nets_argentinian_soccer_rights}}</ref> and [[Brasileirao]].\n[[File:\u0639\u0644\u064a \u0627\u062d\u0645\u062f beINsports.jpg|thumb|right|Former Brazilian striker [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]] being interviewed by the network in December 2014]]\nThe network holds the rights to broadcast all [[UEFA Euro 2012]] and [[UEFA Euro 2016|Euro 2016]] matches on the French pay-TV platform while [[TF1]] and [[M6 (TV channel)|M6]] have the [[free-to-air]] rights to select matches.<ref name=\"euros\"/> The channel also holds rights for the 2014 and 2018 [[FIFA World Cup]], and [[2015 Copa Am\u00e9rica]].\n\nIn the [[United States]], the network holds the rights package for [[Ligue 1]], [[La Liga]], FIFA World Cup qualification rounds in the Americas ([[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONMEBOL)|CONMEBOL]] and [[2018 FIFA World Cup qualification (CONCACAF)|CONCACAF]]), except for home matches by Mexico and the United States (which are both held by [[Univision]] and [[ESPN]]).<ref name=\"beIN SPORTS\">{{cite web|url=http://www.beINsports.tv/getbeIN |title=Get beIN Sport on your television! |accessdate=19 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, beIN Sports bought the broadcasting rights of the Turkish [[S\u00fcper Lig]] until 2022.<ref name=\"beIN SPORTS Turkey Milliyet\">{{cite web|url=http://m.milliyet.com.tr/lig-tv-nin-adi-bein-sports-olarak---2377342-skorerhaber/ |title=Lig TV's Name will Bein Sports|accessdate=11 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe channel's football coverage is notably fronted by [[Richard Keys]] and [[Andy Gray (footballer, born 1955)|Andy Gray]], who moved to Doha after they were sacked from [[Sky Sports]].\n\nTheir appointment saw the Monday Night Football brand, regarded as revolutionary [[infront]] and [[Perform Group]] management when it was devised by the presenters in the 1990s, take a place in the channel's schedule.\n\nKeys and Gray also present an eponymous magazine-style show on Friday evenings and have attracted praise for the variety and quality of proper football men featured on the show.\n\nIn November 2019, Canal+ and beIN Sports won the rights to broadcast Champions League matches in France between 2021 and 2024 for $413 million a year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2019/11/29/business/29reuters-france-soccer-tv.html|title=France-Vivendi's Canal+ and BeIn Regain Champions League Rights|publisher=The New York Times|accessdate=29 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 February 2020, BeIn Sports announced to broadcast special shows and dedicated programs for 1000 days until the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]]. To be broadcast from February 25 on its free-to-air and HD1 channel, the programs were supposed to include historic matches, highlights from the international best players, history of Qatari football and special clips of the day [[Qatar]] won the World Cup bid.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://biz.blogdady.com/bein-sports-activities-to-broadcast-countdown-to-2022-fifa-world-cup-qatar/|title=beIN Sports activities to broadcast countdown to 2022 FIFA World Cup Qatar|accessdate=23 February 2020|website=Business News}}</ref>\n\n===Rugby union===\n\nIn France, beIN Sports broadcasts November test matches, [[European Rugby Champions Cup]], [[European Rugby Challenge Cup]], [[English Premiership (rugby union)|English Premiership]] and [[Pro14]].\n\n===Rugby league===\nbeIN Sports will broadcast the [[Super League]] including all home matches of French side [[Catalans Dragons]].<ref name=\"xiii\">{{cite web |title=Charles Bi\u00e9try : \"15 joueurs par \u00e9quipe, \u00e7a fait beaucoup\" |work=L'Ind\u00e9pendant |url=http://www.lindependant.fr/2012/02/09/charles-bietry-15-joueurs-par-equipe-ca-fait-beaucoup,115930.php |date=2012-02-09 |accessdate=2012-04-30}}</ref> Other competitions include the Australian [[National Rugby League]] and [[State of Origin series]].<ref name=\"xiii\"/>\n\nbeIN Sports was awarded the rights to the [[2013 Rugby League World Cup]] and broadcast all matches live.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.beINsports.fr/news/article/184xh4lrfr0qv1tp49za3wchgu|title=Angleterre \u2013 France sur beIN Sport|work=beinsports.fr|accessdate=11 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Motorsports===\nOn 23 February 2013, as part of Al-Jazeera's increasing footprint in the [[Superbike World Championship]], which they hold rights in the Middle East, and the transitional shutdown of [[Speed Channel|Fox Sports]] motorsport operations in Charlotte, North Carolina, beIN Sports acquired the rights to the Superbike World Championship in the United States, which also includes live coverage of the races and also the support classes, which had never been televised in the United States in the past.<ref>{{cite news |title=World Superbike in US by beIN |url=http://www.worldsbk.com/en/news/5-sbk-news/16192-world-superbike-in-usa-by-beIN.html |work=Dorna |date=2013-02-23 |accessdate=2013-03-06}}</ref>\n\nbeIN Sports also airs the [[FIA World Rallycross Championship]] in the United States, the Middle East, and North Africa.\n\nIn 2016, beIN Sports began to broadcast two more Dorna-controlled motorcycle road racing series in the United States and Canada -- [[MotoGP]], the [[Superbike World Championship]] and [[AMA Superbike Championship|MotoAmerica]], giving them control of FIM road racing on North American television.\n\n===Team handball===\nbeIN Sports has acquired exclusive broadcast rights to the [[EHF Champions League]] ([[Team Handball]]). The EHF Champions League is the most important club competition for men's and women's teams in Europe and involves the leading teams from the top European nations.\n\nIn January 2013, beIN Sports also acquired the broadcast rights to the [[2013 World Men's Handball Championship]]. beIN Sports USA aired live, delayed and pre-recorded [[High-definition television in the United States|HD]] games in the US, between January 11\u201327, 2013.\n\n===Tennis===\nIn France, beIN Sports airs the [[Wimbledon Championships]], [[Davis Cup]], [[Fed Cup]], [[ATP World Tour Masters 1000]], [[ATP World Tour 500]], [[ATP World Tour Finals]], and some [[ATP World Tour 250]] and [[WTA Tour]] tournaments.\n\nbeIN Sports will be the exclusive broadcaster of WTA Tour in the United States, Australia, the Middle East, and North Africa from 2017 to 2021.\n\n===Other sports===\n\nIn France, beIN Sports aired the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] tennis, handball and basketball tournaments. In athletics, beIN Sports airs the [[IAAF Diamond League]] and several international marathons and World Indoor Meetings. In cycling, it broadcasts some [[Union Cycliste Internationale|UCI]] World Tour road races, including the [[Giro d'Italia]], as well as the UCI Road, Track, Mountain Bike and Trials World Championships. The channel also airs the French Handball Championship, [[FIVB World League]], [[Euroleague]], [[NBA]], [[National Football League]], and [[Major League Baseball]].\n\nOn 25 May 2016, the U.S. beIN Sports announced that it had acquired partial rights to [[Conference USA]] [[college sports]], including a package of selected [[college football]], [[college basketball|basketball]], [[College baseball|baseball]], [[College softball|softball]], and [[College soccer|soccer]] matches. The deal marks the first [[American football]]-related contract the U.S. network has acquired.<ref name=\"dnj-beincusa\">{{cite web|title=Getting to know new C-USA TV partner beIN Sports|url=http://www.dnj.com/story/sports/college/mtsu/2016/05/23/getting-know-new-c-usa-tv-partner-bein-sports/84800568/|website=The Daily News Journal|accessdate=24 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, [[cricket]] debuted on the channel. BeIN Sports has acquired the [[Cricket Australia]] and [[England and Wales Cricket Board]] rights for the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region, and broadcast the [[2017\u201318 Ashes series]] and [[2017\u201318 Big Bash League season]].  BeIN Sports also acquired the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL) rights in April 2018 for the Middle East and North Africa (MENA) region in a five-year deal with [[Star India]] up to 2022.\n\nOn 20 April 2018, [[professional wrestling]] debuted on the channel. [[Major League Wrestling]]: FUSION airs on Fridays at 8 pm EST on [[beIN Sports (American TV channel)|beIN Sports USA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mlw.com/2018/04/20/mlw-premieres-tonight-on-bein-sports/|title=MLW premieres tonight on beIN Sports|first=|last=MLW.com|date=20 April 2018|website=MLW: Major League Wrestling\u00ae|access-date=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Football coverage==\n\nA list of on-air football personalities on beIN Sports France, beIN Sports MENA, beIN Sports USA, and beIN Sports Spain:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name !! Role !! Note\n|-\n| [[Darren Tulett]]  || Presenter || Host of ''Sports Night''\n|-\n| [[Jean-Pierre Papin]] || Pundit ||  ''Le Club'' pundit\n|-\n| [[Robert Pires]] || Pundit || ''Le Club'' pundit\n|-\n| [[Patrick Vieira]] || Pundit ||  ''Le Club'' pundit\n|-\n| [[Luis Fernandez]] || Pundit ||  ''Le Club'' pundit\n|-\n| [[Sonny Anderson]] || Pundit ||  ''Le Club'' pundit\n|-\n| [[Ludovic Giuly]] || Pundit ||  ''Le Club'' pundit\n|-\n| [[\u00c9ric Di Meco]] || Commentator || [[Ligue 1]] and [[UEFA Champions League]] co-commentator\n|-\n| [[Patrice Ferri]] || Commentator || [[Ligue 1]], [[FA Cup]], [[Football League Cup]], [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League]] co-commentator\n|-\n| [[Bruno Cheyrou]] || Commentator || [[Ligue 1]], [[Serie A]], [[Coppa Italia]], [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League]] co-commentator\n|-\n| [[Omar Da Fonseca]] || Commentator || [[La Liga]], [[Copa del Rey]], [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League]] co-commentator\n|-\n| [[Jean-Alain Boumsong]] || Commentator || [[Ligue 1]], [[Ligue 2]], [[UEFA Champions League]] and [[UEFA Europa League]] co-commentator\n|-\n| [[Brahim Thiam]] || Commentator || [[Ligue 1]] and [[UEFA Europa League]] co-commentator\n|-\n| [[Gernot Rohr]] || Commentator || [[Bundesliga]] co-commentator\n|-\n| [[Ray Hudson]] || Commentator || [[La Liga]] color commentator\n|-\n| [[Terri Leigh]] || Presenter || Host of ''The Express''\n|-\n| [[Angus Scott (television presenter)|Angus Scott]] || Anchor || Presenter of [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] Football\n|-\n| [[Andy Gray (footballer, born 1955)|Andy Gray]] || Analyst || Co-presenter of English Premier League Football\n|-\n| [[Andy Kerr (television presenter)|Andy Kerr]] 